a from physical, social, technological, economic, political, and ethical / religious perspectives. Interpreting and summarizing the large and complex literatures from each of these disciplines, the book offers a multidisciplinary approach to the challenges we face in Canada. Special attention is given to Canada’s response to the Kyoto Protocol, as well as an assessment of the overall adequacy of Kyoto as a response to the global challenge of climate change. Hard Choices fills a gap in available books which provide readers with reliable information on climate change and its impacts that are specific to Canada. While written for the general reader, it is also well suited for use as an undergraduate text in environmental studies courses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnvironmental Studies. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBass, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruce, James P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Stewart J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Stewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoward, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoward, Harold, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEtkin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacroix, Jacinthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLivingston, Nigel J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLonergan, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLove, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab